\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subsidies have been unpopular because they are believed to induce excessive
 risks-taking from framers.
 Although studies suggest that the poor are not at all more likely to spend
 on risky projects, the route of subsidies remains an area susceptible to
 contest and doubtful effectiveness.
 Employment guarantee schemes seem a better approach due to their appeal
 of low enforcement costs.
 However, for both the methods, the biggest hurdle seems to be that of cost.
 With limited sources, struggles in a fair allocation of limited resources
 may leave the poorest unaffected through such schemes.
